 is possible</td></tr></table></td><td><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody">On Tue, Oct 31, 2017 at 9:15 AM, Marc Gonzalez<br />&lt;marc_gonzalez&#64;sigmadesigns.com&gt; wrote:<br />&gt;<br />&gt; On arm32, it is possible to set up udelay() to be clock-based.<br /><br />I'm not sure why this is discussed as some kind of generic problem.<br /><br />Just do what x86-64 already does. We use the TSC, and ndelay() does<br />the right thing too.<br /><br />I've not checked precision, but it should be close to the TSC update<br />frequency. So we're talking tens of megahertz.<br /><br />Does it work on all PC's? No. It's only half-way reliable on the ones<br />where the TSC frequency doesn't change. So there are no *guarantees*.<br /><br />               Linus<br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
